What are the different precision options available for weights and activations in the quantizer?,"Section: # Quantizer
## Basic Quantization Methods
Content:
### Fixed Precision Quantization
Applies static uniform quantization to both weights and activations. Users can specify the precision (bit-width) for weights and activations. The entire model is quantized to the specified precision.
### Mixed Precision Quantization
Allows different parts of the model to use different precisions
Two approaches are supported:
- Mixed precision by name: Users specify precisions for specific activation or weight names

- Mixed precision by operator: Users define precisions for different types of operators. For example, if set the Add operator to INT4 then all outputs of the Add operators are quantized to INT4; Section: Quantizer
# Quantizer
## Basic Quantization Methods
Content:
### Fixed Precision Quantization
Applies static uniform quantization to both weights and activations. Users can specify the precision (bit-width) for weights and activations. The entire model is quantized to the specified precision
### Mixed Precision Quantization
Allows different parts of the model to use different precisions
Two approaches are supported:
- Mixed precision by name: Users specify precisions for specific activation or weight names

- Mixed precision by operator: Users define precisions for different types of operators. For example, if set the Add operator to INT4 then all outputs of the Add operators are quantized to INT4; Section: # Quantizer
Content:
## Advanced Quantization Methods
Currently supported advanced quantization methods are as follows.
- Softmax Bias Correction (https://arxiv.org/abs/2309.01729)

column2: - A method that add a float bias to Softmax output layer to reduce the performance degradation caused by quantization

column1: - SmoothQuant (https://arxiv.org/abs/2211.10438)

column2: - A method that smooths the activation outliers by offline migrating the quantization difficulty from activations to weights with a mathematically equivalent transformation

column1: - Cross Layer Equalization (https://arxiv.org/abs/1906.04721)

column2: - A method that tune the weights range of the channels in one tensor to reduce quantization error

column1: - Dummy Convolution for the Concat Operator

column2: - The dummy conv algorithm can be applied during the fixed or mixed precision quantization process. It adds a dummy convolution operator to the long residual input activations of the concat operator by a specific algorithm to maintain the long residual input activation scales. After applying this method, the model perfromance could be improved.

column1: ## Debug API
### Layer-wise mixed precision quantiztion debug API

The quantizer provides a mixed precision quantization debug API. Users can select different activations and weights and assign them varying levels of precision. The input includes a quantized CNNX model and a debug dictionary.; Section: # Quantizer
Content:

Quantizer is a module in EHT that applies basic and advanced quantization methods to input models. Basic methods include fixed precision quantization and mixed precision quantization (MPQ). Users can apply mixed precision quantization to models by specifying activation names or operators. Quantizer also provides a MPQ debug API.; Section: Quantizer
# Quantizer
Content:

Quantizer is a module in EHT that applies basic and advanced quantization methods to input models. Basic methods include fixed precision quantization and mixed precision quantization. Users can apply mixed precision quantization to models by specifying activation names or operators.; Section: Quantizer

Specify the type of the input model. Optimization is performed differently depending on the model type, with details as follows
- CV

- **precision_activation : str** : precision of activation(ex. int8, int16, fp16)

## **Detailed explanation for optimization yaml file**
Content:
input_model_path : string**
Specify the file path of the input model. You must specify the file, not the parent folder.
**output_folder_path : string**
This is the path where the output will be saved.
**model_type : string**
Specify the type of the input model. Optimization is performed differently depending on the model type, with details as follows
- CV
- LVM
- LLM
**quantizer : dict**
- **precision_weight : int** : precision of weight
- **precision_activation : int** : precision of activation

- **mpq_operator_dict : dict** : When performing mixed precision quantization, input the operators and precision to be quantized with a precision different from the values specified in precision_weight and precision_activation above.; Section: # **How to use**
## **Detailed explanation for elt yaml file**
Content:
- **do_quantize : bool** : Enable quantization
- **eltsum_cvt : bool** : enable eltwise conversion process; eltsum -> concat + conv
- **graph_opt : str** : Graph Optimizer Model Type, Model Name for Graph Optimizer.
- **mean : str** : Mean value(s), for multiple channel ""128, 128, 128, ..."" / y=x-MEAN
- **onnx_simplify : bool** : enable onnx_simplify process
- **optimize : bool** : Use graph optimization
- **quantize_type : str** : Select quantization type, quantized model (include caffeQAT) is ""qat""
- **scale : str** : Scale value(s), for multiple channel ""128, 128, 128, ..."" / ex> y=x/SCALE
- **bw_ofm : int** : Bitwidth of intermediate feature map(A).; Section: Dataset preparation

Content:
This is a guideline for preparing the input dataset for the simulator and calibration dataset for the quantizer module.
## **Detailed instruction for dataset preparation**
Analyze model inputs using Netron. The example model receives three inputs: encoder_hidden_states, sample, and timestep.

Create a JSON file named 'input_folder_mapping.json'. In this file, define key-value pairs where each key represents a model input name and its corresponding value is the name of the folder containing the input data for that model input.
```json
After preparing the dataset and JSON file, create a dataset directory and place it in the specified location.
It's important to note that the file names for each input should be identical, as shown in the example above.

Currently, the supported data type is npy files consisting of float type. Support for other data formats is planned for the future.| Data Format | Support |

column1: Content:
Simulator conducts inference on a CNNX model, which contains an ONNX model file and a quantization information encodings file. It can check output and intermediate tensors during execution.

Quantized inference is performed using _simulated quantization_. Simulated quantization provides the capability to mimic the effects of quantized operations. Floating point values are clipped and divided into several ranges, and values within each range are converted to the same value, simulating the quantization process.

Simulator includes the following features(with example codes):","The purpose of applying Fixed Precision Quantization to the optimized CNNX model is to reduce the model size and computational requirements, allowing it to run efficiently on hardware with limited resources. This process involves converting the model's parameters from high precision (such as floating-point) to a lower precision (such as 8-bit integers), which can lead to faster inference times and reduced power consumption. Additionally, Fixed Precision Quantization can help in keeping the model's performance (accuracy) comparable to its original form by optimizing the precision level for different parts of the model.","The purpose of applying Fixed Precision Quantization to the optimized CNNX model is to perform quantization, which typically involves reducing the precision of the model's weights and activations to improve efficiency, such as reducing model size and increasing inference speed.",0,0.00498,0.54013,
Why is it important for the keys in the h5 dataset to match the input names of the model?,"Content:
# **Dataset preparation**
This is a guideline for preparing the input dataset.
## **Dataset format**
The dataset format must use the .h5 file extension. It is important to ensure that the keys in the h5 dataset match the input names of the model for proper mapping to occur.
Additionally, as the Exynos AI Studio currently only accepts float32 data types, the internal data within the h5 file must be in fp32 format.
The h5 file should be placed directly under the DATA folder, which is generated after executing the 'enntools init' command in the workspace.
# Model Requirements and Constraints
## model format
- Model should be prepared in ONNX format to start optimization.
## opset version
- EHT currently support ONNX opset version 13 ~ 17.; Section: Dataset preparation

Content:
- **metric : string**: The metric to be used for measurement
- **threshold : float** : The threshold value of the metric that determines agreement / disagreement
- **input_data_path : string**: The path to the dataset for model inference
**optimizer : dict**
- **skip_4_dim_conversion : bool** : If true, it does not convert to 4 dimensions before optimization; if false, it proceeds with the conversion.
- **overwrite_input_shapes : dict** : Enter the input shape for models with undefined input shapes.

- **custom_template_path : dict**: Enter the templates to apply for optimization. Use the path of the Python file containing the template as the key, and the template within it as the value.; Section: ENN SDK Developer Guide

## 5. Advanced Topics
### Model Design Tips
Content:
#### Data Processing Procedures
- **Pre-processing** and **Post-processing**: Implement these tasks outside the main model computation.

column2: For efficient execution, it is recommended to use parallel processing on GPU or CPU.

column1: - **Memory Alignment**: Includes data transformation operations such as `split` and `reshape` during the pre-processing phase to ensure proper data alignment.
#### Layer Adjustments
To enhance performance, it is recommended to exclude the dropout layer.
#### PReLU
Use the `PReLU` activation function for optimal performance.
Although `LeakyReLU` is functional, it may not provide the same level of efficiency.
#### Sharing IFM and OFM Recursively
Merge successive concatenate layers that share the same Input Feature Maps (IFM) and Output Feature Maps (OFM).; Section: Model Requirements and Constraints

Content:
### activation encodings & param encodings

Encodings information for quantization is given as a json data. For each ONNX activation & params name, bitwidth, dtype, and quantization parameters(min, max, offset, scale, is_symmetric) are given in this part.
### quantizer_args
Global quantization information is given on this part including per_channel_quantization and quantization scheme.
### modules

Module information after EHT optimizer is given on this part. Under the module name as a key, SNC layer information(SNC_OP, SNC_params) and ONNX element related to the module(Elements) are given.; Section: Writing Native Program

column1: 1. **Optimization**: The CNNX model is first passed through a simplifier and a 4-dimensional conversion process. An optimization template is then applied to the model. The output of this step is stored at `{result_dir}/cnnx`.

# Quantizer
## Basic Quantization Methods
Content:
### Fixed Precision Quantization
Applies static uniform quantization to both weights and activations. Users can specify the precision (bit-width) for weights and activations. The entire model is quantized to the specified precision
### Mixed Precision Quantization
Allows different parts of the model to use different precisions
Two approaches are supported:
- Mixed precision by name: Users specify precisions for specific activation or weight names

- Mixed precision by operator: Users define precisions for different types of operators. For example, if set the Add operator to INT4 then all outputs of the Add operators are quantized to INT4; Section: # Quantizer

Quantized inference is performed using _simulated quantization_. Simulated quantization provides the capability to mimic the effects of quantized operations. # Simulator
Content:
Simulator conducts inference on a CNNX model, which contains an ONNX model file and a quantization information encodings file. It can check output and intermediate tensors during execution.

Quantized inference is performed using _simulated quantization_. Simulated quantization provides the capability to mimic the effects of quantized operations. Floating point values are clipped and divided into several ranges, and values within each range are converted to the same value, simulating the quantization process.
Simulator includes the following features:
- `get_quantization_sim`: Attain a CNNX quantization simulation session for manual run.
- `load_input_data`: Load the input data from the given dataset path.
- `run_inference`: Conduct inference on a CNNX model.
- `compare_model_by_inference`: Compare two CNNX models on their inference outputs. Currently, the SNR value is used for the comparison metric.
- `compare_model_by_layer` (TBD): Compare two CNNX models on intermediate tensors for each layer. To be released.; Section: # **How to use**

- **mpq_operator_dict : dict** : When performing mixed precision quantization, input the operators and precision to be quantized with a precision different from the values specified in precision_weight and precision_activation above.

# **Dataset preparation**
This is a guideline for preparing the input dataset.
## **Dataset format**
The dataset format must use the .h5 file extension. It is important to ensure that the keys in the h5 dataset match the input names of the model for proper mapping to occur.
Additionally, as the Exynos AI Studio currently only accepts float32 data types, the internal data within the h5 file must be in fp32 format.
The h5 file should be placed directly under the DATA folder, which is generated after executing the 'enntools init' command in the workspace.

Encodings information for quantization is given as a json data. For each ONNX activation & params name, bitwidth, dtype, and quantization parameters(min, max, offset, scale, is_symmetric) are given in this part.

Under the module name as a key, SNC layer information(SNC_OP, SNC_params) and ONNX element related to the module(Elements) are given.; Question: I would like to know which operators are supported by the ENN SDK when developing Pose Estimation.

Answer: For the Pose Estimation category, the supported operators include CONVOLUTION, RELU, and CONCATENATION.; Question: I would like to know which operators are supported by the ENN SDK when developing Computer Vision for Healthcare.

Answer: For the Computer Vision for Healthcare category, the supported operators include CONVOLUTION, MAXPOOL, AVGPOOL, RESHAPE, and CONCATENATION.; Question: I would like to know the ENN SDK support models and environments.

Answer: The ENN SDK facilitates AI model development by supporting various models, primarily focusing on TensorFlow Lite compatibility. It advises the conversion of TensorFlow Lite models through MLIR (Multi-Level Intermediate Representation) version 1.14 or higher, accommodating models with up to four dimensions and a maximum size of 1 GB. For models targeted for the Neural Processing Unit (NPU), quantization is mandatory, and model distillation is advised for optimization. This SDK is crafted to provide flexibility and comprehensive support, ensuring wide compatibility and adaptability across diverse AI applications and usage scenarios.; Section: Exynos AI Studio User Guide (TBD)

# Simulator
Content:
Simulator conducts inference on a CNNX model, which contains an ONNX model file and a quantization information encodings file. It can check output and intermediate tensors during execution.

Quantized inference is performed using _simulated quantization_. Simulated quantization provides the capability to mimic the effects of quantized operations. Floating point values are clipped and divided into several ranges, and values within each range are converted to the same value, simulating the quantization process.
Simulator includes the following features:
- `get_quantization_sim`: Attain a CNNX quantization simulation session for manual run.
- `load_input_data`: Load the input data from the given dataset path.
- `run_inference`: Conduct inference on a CNNX model.
- `compare_model_by_inference`: Compare two CNNX models on their inference outputs. Currently, the SNR value is used for the comparison metric.
- `compare_model_by_layer` (TBD): Compare two CNNX models on intermediate tensors for each layer. To be released.; Section: Model Requirements and Constraints

column4: }","To compare two CNNX models using their inference outputs and intermediate tensors, you can use the simulator tool provided by the ENN SDK. Here’s how you can do it based on the provided context:

column1: 1. **Compare Inference Outputs**:
- Use the `compare_model_by_inference` function from the simulator to compare the outputs of the two models. The Signal-to-Noise Ratio (SNR) is used as the metric for comparison.
2. **Compare Intermediate Tensors**:

- Use the `compare_model_by_layer` function to compare the intermediate tensors for each layer of the two CNNX models. This involves comparing the feature maps at various layers to ensure that the models perform similarly on intermediate levels as well.
For example, here’s a Python snippet using `compare_model_by_layer` to compare intermediate tensors for each layer:
```python
from simulator import api
params = api.LayerwiseCheckerParameters(
input_data_path=""/path/to/input/data"",
input_model_path_0=""/path/to/model/0.onnx"",
input_encodings_path_0=""/path/to/model/0.encodings"",
input_model_path_1=""/path/to/model/1.onnx"",
input_encodings_path_1=""/path/to/model/1.encodings"",
metric=""snr"",
threshold=100,
use_cuda=False,
layer_match_info=[(""featuremap_0"", ""featuremap_0""), (""featuremap_1"", ""featuremap_1"")],
export_featuremap=True,
export_featuremap_path=""/path/to/save/exported/featuremap""
res = api.compare_model_by_layer(params)
print(""Layerwise check:"")
for input_name, result in res.items():
_, result_dict = result
for output_name, snr_value in result_dict.items():
print(f""{output_name}: {snr_value}"")

In this example, the `layer_match_info` is used to specify which feature maps should be compared between the two models. Adjust the paths and parameters according to your specific models and data.","Two CNNX models can be compared using their inference outputs by using the `compare_model_by_inference` feature, which uses the SNR value as the comparison metric. They can also be compared using their intermediate tensors for each layer by using the `compare_model_by_layer` feature.",0.69643,0.00463,0.61303,

# Introduction to Exynos AI Studio

Exynos AI Studio** is a software that provides optimization and conversion techniques for neural networks models. This software takes models as input and offers functionalities such as quantization, conversion, optimization, compilation to generate NNC models.
## System overview diagram; Section: # Quantizer
Content:

Quantizer is a module in EHT that applies basic and advanced quantization methods to input models. Basic methods include fixed precision quantization and mixed precision quantization (MPQ). Users can apply mixed precision quantization to models by specifying activation names or operators. Quantizer also provides a MPQ debug API.; Section: Quantizer
# Quantizer

Quantizer is a module in EHT that applies basic and advanced quantization methods to input models. Basic methods include fixed precision quantization and mixed precision quantization. Content:

Currently supported advanced quantization methods are as follows.
- Softmax Bias Correction (https://arxiv.org/abs/2309.01729)

column2: - A method that add a float bias to Softmax output layer to reduce the performance degradation caused by quantization

column1: - SmoothQuant (https://arxiv.org/abs/2211.10438)

column2: - A method that smooths the activation outliers by offline migrating the quantization difficulty from activations to weights with a mathematically equivalent transformation

column1: - Cross Layer Equalization (https://arxiv.org/abs/1906.04721)

column2: - A method that tune the weights range of the channels in one tensor to reduce quantization error

column1: - Dummy Convolution for the Concat Operator

column2: - The dummy conv algorithm can be applied during the fixed or mixed precision quantization process. It adds a dummy convolution operator to the long residual input activations of the concat operator by a specific algorithm to maintain the long residual input activation scales. After applying this method, the model perfromance could be improved.

column1: # Quantizer
## Basic Quantization Methods
Content:
### Fixed Precision Quantization
Applies static uniform quantization to both weights and activations. Users can specify the precision (bit-width) for weights and activations. The entire model is quantized to the specified precision
### Mixed Precision Quantization
Allows different parts of the model to use different precisions
Two approaches are supported:
- Mixed precision by name: Users specify precisions for specific activation or weight names

- Mixed precision by operator: Users define precisions for different types of operators. For example, if set the Add operator to INT4 then all outputs of the Add operators are quantized to INT4; Content:

It offers both basic and advanced quantization methods to optimize neural network models. The basic methods include fixed precision quantization, where the entire model is quantized to a specified precision, and mixed precision quantization, which allows different parts of the model to use different precisions. Advanced quantization methods supported include:
1. **Softmax Bias Correction**: Adds a float bias to the Softmax output layer to reduce performance degradation due to quantization.
2. **SmoothQuant**: Smooths activation outliers by transferring quantization difficulty from activations to weights.
3. **Cross Layer Equalization**: Tunes the weight range across channels to reduce quantization error.
4. **Dummy Convolution for Concat Operator**: Improves model performance by adjusting scales of long residual inputs in the quantization process.

Quantization in Exynos AI Studio helps improve model efficiency by reducing computational and memory requirements while maintaining performance.",The answer to given question is not present in context,0.77143,0.0102,0.17143,

column1: ## **Detailed explanation for elt yaml file**
Content:
- **do_quantize : bool** : Enable quantization
- **eltsum_cvt : bool** : enable eltwise conversion process; eltsum -> concat + conv
- **graph_opt : str** : Graph Optimizer Model Type, Model Name for Graph Optimizer.
- **mean : str** : Mean value(s), for multiple channel ""128, 128, 128, ..."" / y=x-MEAN
- **onnx_simplify : bool** : enable onnx_simplify process
- **optimize : bool** : Use graph optimization
- **quantize_type : str** : Select quantization type, quantized model (include caffeQAT) is ""qat""
- **scale : str** : Scale value(s), for multiple channel ""128, 128, 128, ..."" / ex> y=x/SCALE
- **bw_ofm : int** : Bitwidth of intermediate feature map(A).; Section: Model Requirements and Constraints

Content:
### activation encodings & param encodings

Encodings information for quantization is given as a json data. For each ONNX activation & params name, bitwidth, dtype, and quantization parameters(min, max, offset, scale, is_symmetric) are given in this part.
### quantizer_args
Global quantization information is given on this part including per_channel_quantization and quantization scheme.
### modules

Module information after EHT optimizer is given on this part. Under the module name as a key, SNC layer information(SNC_OP, SNC_params) and ONNX element related to the module(Elements) are given.; Section: Frontend API
# **Frontend API**
## **Detailed explanation for optimization yaml file**
Content:
input_model_path : string**
Specify the file path of the input model. You must specify the file, not the parent folder.
**output_folder_path : string**
This is the path where the output will be saved.
**model_type : string**
Specify the type of the input model. Optimization is performed differently depending on the model type, with details as follows
- CV
- LVM
- LLM
**quantizer : dict**
- **precision_weight : int** : precision of weight
- **precision_activation : int** : precision of activation

- **mpq_operator_dict : dict** : When performing mixed precision quantization, input the operators and precision to be quantized with a precision different from the values specified in precision_weight and precision_activation above.","Users can apply mixed precision quantization (MPQ) to models using the Quantizer module in EHT by following these steps:
1. **Choose the Approach**: MPQ can be applied in two ways:
- **Mixed precision by name**: Specify precisions for specific activation or weight names.
- **Mixed precision by operator**: Define precisions for different types of operators. For example, you can set the Add operator to INT4, which quantizes all outputs of the Add operators to INT4.
2. **Configure the YAML File**:
- In the `quantizer` section of your YAML configuration file, you need to specify the following:
- **precision_weight**: Define the general precision for weights (e.g., int8, int16, fp16).
- **precision_activation**: Define the general precision for activations (e.g., int8, int16, fp16).
- **mpq_operator_dict**: Specify a dictionary where you input the operators and precisions to be quantized differently from the specified general precisions for weights and activations.

By configuring these parameters, you can control which parts of your model use different precisions, allowing for optimized performance and resource efficiency.",Users can apply mixed precision quantization to models by specifying activation names or operators.,0.85714,0.03968,0.39639,

This involves clipping and dividing floating point values into several ranges, where values within each range are converted to the same value. This simulation allows for testing and verifying the behavior of quantized models by simulating how they would perform if actual quantized arithmetic were used. This can be useful for understanding the potential impact of quantization on model performance and accuracy before implementing actual quantized execution.","Simulated quantization provides the capability to mimic the effects of quantized operations. Floating point values are clipped and divided into several ranges, and values within each range are converted to the same value, simulating the quantization process.",0.4,0.01538,0.60093,

Content:
# Introduction to Exynos AI High-Level Toolchain (EHT)

EHT** is a software that provides optimization techniques for neural networks, including computer vision (CV) models, large language models (LLM), and large vision models (LVM). This software takes models as input and offers functionalities such as quantization and model optimization to generate SNC models.
## System overview diagram; Section: # **How to use**
## **Detailed explanation for elt yaml file**
Content:
- **do_quantize : bool** : Enable quantization
- **eltsum_cvt : bool** : enable eltwise conversion process; eltsum -> concat + conv
- **graph_opt : str** : Graph Optimizer Model Type, Model Name for Graph Optimizer.
- **mean : str** : Mean value(s), for multiple channel ""128, 128, 128, ..."" / y=x-MEAN
- **onnx_simplify : bool** : enable onnx_simplify process
- **optimize : bool** : Use graph optimization
- **quantize_type : str** : Select quantization type, quantized model (include caffeQAT) is ""qat""
- **scale : str** : Scale value(s), for multiple channel ""128, 128, 128, ..."" / ex> y=x/SCALE
- **bw_ofm : int** : Bitwidth of intermediate feature map(A).; Section: # **How to use**
## **Detailed explanation for eht yaml file**
Content:
model_type : string**
Specify the type of the input model. Optimization is performed differently depending on the model type, with details as follows
- CV
- LVM
- LLM
**quantizer : dict**
- **precision_weight : str** : precision of weight(ex. int8, int16, fp16)
- **precision_activation : str** : precision of activation(ex. int8, int16, fp16)

- **mpq_operator_dict : dict** : When performing mixed precision quantization, input the operators and precision to be quantized with a precision different from the values specified in precision_weight and precision_activation above.
- **alpha : float** : smoothquant migration strength; Section: Model Requirements and Constraints
# Model Requirements and Constraints
Content:
## model format
- Model should be prepared in CNNX or ONNX format to start optimization.
- ONNX file should be converted into CNNX format using converter module.

column2: - EHT accepts ONNX external data for tensors. External data files should be in the same directory as the [.onnx] file.
- The [.onnx] file size is limited to 2GB. For files larger than 2GB, the model should be saved using external data format.

column1: ## opset version
- EHT currently support ONNX opset version ≤ 18, but ≤ 16 for stable usage.; Section: # Quantizer
Content:
## Advanced Quantization Methods
Currently supported advanced quantization methods are as follows.
- Softmax Bias Correction (https://arxiv.org/abs/2309.01729)

column2: - A method that add a float bias to Softmax output layer to reduce the performance degradation caused by quantization

column1: - SmoothQuant (https://arxiv.org/abs/2211.10438)

column2: - A method that smooths the activation outliers by offline migrating the quantization difficulty from activations to weights with a mathematically equivalent transformation

column1: - Cross Layer Equalization (https://arxiv.org/abs/1906.04721)

column2: - A method that tune the weights range of the channels in one tensor to reduce quantization error

column1: - Dummy Convolution for the Concat Operator

column2: - The dummy conv algorithm can be applied during the fixed or mixed precision quantization process. It adds a dummy convolution operator to the long residual input activations of the concat operator by a specific algorithm to maintain the long residual input activation scales. After applying this method, the model perfromance could be improved.

The quantizer provides a mixed precision quantization debug API. Users can select different activations and weights and assign them varying levels of precision. The input includes a quantized CNNX model and a debug dictionary.; Section: Quantizer

column1: # Model Requirements and Constraints
## CNNX model
Content:
### activation encodings & param encodings

Encodings information for quantization is given as a json data. For each ONNX activation & params name, bitwidth, dtype, and quantization parameters(min, max, offset, scale, is_symmetric) are given in this part.
### quantizer_args
Global quantization information is given on this part including per_channel_quantization and quantization scheme.
### modules

Module information after EHT optimizer is given on this part. Under the module name as a key, SNC layer information(SNC_OP, SNC_params) and ONNX element related to the module(Elements) are given.","The EHT (Exynos AI High-Level Toolchain) software provides several functionalities for neural networks, particularly in terms of quantization and model optimization. These include:

1. **Quantization**: EHT has a Quantizer module that applies both basic and advanced quantization methods to input models. Basic methods include fixed precision quantization and mixed precision quantization (MPQ). Advanced methods supported are Softmax Bias Correction, SmoothQuant, Cross Layer Equalization, and Dummy Convolution for the Concat Operator.

2. **Model Optimization**: EHT can optimize models by applying techniques suitable for computer vision (CV), large language models (LLM), and large vision models (LVM). These optimizations help generate SNC models that are better suited for performance on neural networks.

3. **Quantization Debugging**: EHT provides a mixed precision quantization debug API, allowing users to specify different levels of precision for activations and weights, and perform detailed debugging on the quantized models.

Overall, these functionalities aim to improve neural network performance by optimizing and fine-tuning model parameters and structures for better efficiency and accuracy.",EHT software offers functionalities such as quantization and model optimization for neural networks.,0.79224,0.13889,0.29196,
How can different precisions be utilized in a model using mixed precision approaches?,"Section: # Quantizer
## Basic Quantization Methods
Content:
### Fixed Precision Quantization
Applies static uniform quantization to both weights and activations. Users can specify the precision (bit-width) for weights and activations. The entire model is quantized to the specified precision.
### Mixed Precision Quantization
Allows different parts of the model to use different precisions
Two approaches are supported:
- Mixed precision by name: Users specify precisions for specific activation or weight names

- Mixed precision by operator: Users define precisions for different types of operators. For example, if set the Add operator to INT4 then all outputs of the Add operators are quantized to INT4; Section: Quantizer

# ENN SDK Developer Guide
## 5. Advanced Topics
### Model Design Tips
Content:
#### Data Processing Procedures
- **Pre-processing** and **Post-processing**: Implement these tasks outside the main model computation.

column2: For efficient execution, it is recommended to use parallel processing on GPU or CPU.

column1: - **Memory Alignment**: Includes data transformation operations such as `split` and `reshape` during the pre-processing phase to ensure proper data alignment.
#### Layer Adjustments
To enhance performance, it is recommended to exclude the dropout layer.
#### PReLU
Use the `PReLU` activation function for optimal performance.
Although `LeakyReLU` is functional, it may not provide the same level of efficiency.
#### Sharing IFM and OFM Recursively
Merge successive concatenate layers that share the same Input Feature Maps (IFM) and Output Feature Maps (OFM).; Section: # Optimizer
Content:

Models are trained and generated on floating-point hardware like CPUs and GPUs. These devices generally perform well, but not for chips due to hardware constraints. Optimizer provides optimization methods for these models to perform best on Exynos chips. Optimizer supports three powerful features.
- shape_inference

column2: If the input shape is not specified or need to be changed, shape_inference allows the user to define/modify it.

column1: - 4dim conversion

column2: To deploy a model with a .nnc extension on a device, all operators must have input and output shapes with four dimensions. To facilitate this, the 4D conversion process identifies and converts all channel axes of the operators to 4D while maintaining their original structure and channel axes. ; Section: # **How to use**

1. **Mixed Precision by Name**: This method allows users to specify different precisions for particular activation or weight names in a model.

2. **Mixed Precision by Operator**: Users define different precisions for various types of operators. For example, you can set all outputs of the Add operator to INT4, thereby quantizing them to this precision.

These approaches enable different parts of the model to use different precisions, potentially optimizing performance and efficiency.","Different precisions can be utilized in a model using mixed precision approaches by specifying precisions for specific activation or weight names, or by defining precisions for different types of operators, such as setting the Add operator to INT4, which quantizes all outputs of the Add operators to INT4.",0.8,0.04237,0.65953,

column1: # Quantizer
## Basic Quantization Methods
Content:
### Fixed Precision Quantization
Applies static uniform quantization to both weights and activations. Users can specify the precision (bit-width) for weights and activations. The entire model is quantized to the specified precision
### Mixed Precision Quantization
Allows different parts of the model to use different precisions
Two approaches are supported:
- Mixed precision by name: Users specify precisions for specific activation or weight names

- Mixed precision by operator: Users define precisions for different types of operators. For example, if set the Add operator to INT4 then all outputs of the Add operators are quantized to INT4; Content:

EHT** is a software that provides optimization techniques for neural networks, including computer vision (CV) models, large language models (LLM), and large vision models (LVM). Content:
Simulator conducts inference on a CNNX model, which contains an ONNX model file and a quantization information encodings file. It can check output and intermediate tensors during execution.

Quantized inference is performed using _simulated quantization_. Simulated quantization provides the capability to mimic the effects of quantized operations. Floating point values are clipped and divided into several ranges, and values within each range are converted to the same value, simulating the quantization process.

Answer: ENN SDK is a software development kit for the Exynos chipset developed by Samsung S.LSI. It is designed to optimize and implement AI and machine learning models on Exynos-based device. Key features include model optimization for Exynos chipsets, support for various AI algorithms, and user-friendly interface improvement. It is primarily aimed at use on mobile devices and aims to provide developers with efficient tools through continuous updates and improvement.; Question: I want to know about ENN SDK.

Answer: The ENN SDK (Exynos Neural Network Software Development Kit) is a software development kit developed by Samsung S.LSI for its Exynos chipset. It is specifically designed to optimize and implement AI and machine learning models on Exynos-based device. The SDK facilitates the conversion and optimization of AI models to be compatible and efficient on devices powered by Exynos processor.; Section: ENN SDK Developer Guide
# ENN SDK Developer Guide
## 2. Features
Content:
### Workflow of ENN SDK
Using ENN SDK involves the following two steps:
1. The user converts NN models to NNC models.

column2: NNC is an NN model format that can run efficiently in Samsung Exynos hardware.

column1: 2. The user executes the converted model for inference.
#### Model Conversion
Use one of the tools that is provided to convert NN models.
To convert a model:
1. Prepare a pre-trained NN model.
2. Set parameters for tools.
3. Execute tools for conversion.
#### Model Execution
Executing converted models is performed by the ENN framework.
When using the ENN framework:
1. Initialize ENN framework.
2. Load the converted model to ENN framework.
3. Allocate and commit all the necessary buffers for the model.
Then:
1. Copy input data to input buffers.
2. Execute model on ENN framework.
3. Use data on output buffers.

column2: > To execute the model multiple times, repeat this process.

column1: Finally, perform the following steps:
1. Uncommit and release buffers allocated to the model.
2. Unload the model.
3. De initialize ENN framework.
ENN framework APIs support language binding for C++.
### Supported Neural Network Models
ENN SDK supports the following NN models:
- TensorFlow Lite
- Tensors with up to four dimensions
- Models with a maximum size of 1 GB
For more information on supported TensorFlow Lite operations, refer to the Support Matrix.; Content:
# **Dataset preparation**
This is a guideline for preparing the input dataset.
## **Dataset format**
The dataset format must use the .h5 file extension. It is important to ensure that the keys in the h5 dataset match the input names of the model for proper mapping to occur.
Additionally, as the Exynos AI Studio currently only accepts float32 data types, the internal data within the h5 file must be in fp32 format.
The h5 file should be placed directly under the DATA folder, which is generated after executing the 'enntools init' command in the workspace.
# Model Requirements and Constraints
## model format
- Model should be prepared in ONNX format to start optimization.
## opset version
- EHT currently support ONNX opset version 13 ~ 17.; Section: # Optimizer
Content:

Models are trained and generated on floating-point hardware like CPUs and GPUs. These devices generally perform well, but not for chips due to hardware constraints. Optimizer provides optimization methods for these models to perform best on Exynos chips. Optimizer supports three powerful features.
- shape_inference

column2: If the input shape is not specified or need to be changed, shape_inference allows the user to define/modify it.

column1: - 4dim conversion

column2: To deploy a model with a .nnc extension on a device, all operators must have input and output shapes with four dimensions. To facilitate this, the 4D conversion process identifies and converts all channel axes of the operators to 4D while maintaining their original structure and channel axes. ; Question: Please tell us about the advantages of ENN SDK compared to other SDKs?

column1: Answer: The AI Toolset provided by each chipset is optimized for each chipset. ENN SDK is also optimized for Exynos chipset. Additionally, it is also used as an optimization tool for Samsung mobile device. # Quantizer
## Basic Quantization Methods
Content:
### Fixed Precision Quantization
Applies static uniform quantization to both weights and activations. Users can specify the precision (bit-width) for weights and activations. The entire model is quantized to the specified precision
### Mixed Precision Quantization
Allows different parts of the model to use different precisions
Two approaches are supported:
- Mixed precision by name: Users specify precisions for specific activation or weight names

- Mixed precision by operator: Users define precisions for different types of operators. For example, if set the Add operator to INT4 then all outputs of the Add operators are quantized to INT4; Section: # Quantizer

Currently supported advanced quantization methods are as follows.
- Softmax Bias Correction (https://arxiv.org/abs/2309.01729)

column2: - A method that add a float bias to Softmax output layer to reduce the performance degradation caused by quantization

column1: - SmoothQuant (https://arxiv.org/abs/2211.10438)

column2: - A method that smooths the activation outliers by offline migrating the quantization difficulty from activations to weights with a mathematically equivalent transformation

column1: - Cross Layer Equalization (https://arxiv.org/abs/1906.04721)

column2: - A method that tune the weights range of the channels in one tensor to reduce quantization error

column1: - Dummy Convolution for the Concat Operator

column2: - The dummy conv algorithm can be applied during the fixed or mixed precision quantization process. It adds a dummy convolution operator to the long residual input activations of the concat operator by a specific algorithm to maintain the long residual input activation scales. After applying this method, the model perfromance could be improved.

Quantized inference is performed using _simulated quantization_. Simulated quantization provides the capability to mimic the effects of quantized operations. ### activation encodings & param encodings

Encodings information for quantization is given as a json data. For each ONNX activation & params name, bitwidth, dtype, and quantization parameters(min, max, offset, scale, is_symmetric) are given in this part.

column1: Example codes to use them:
```python
from converter import api
cnnx_to_snc_params = api.Cnnx2SncParameters(
api.Converter.cnnx_to_snc(cnnx_to_snc_params)
tflite_to_onnx_params = api.TfLite2OnnxParameters(

```","The conversion from CNNX to SNC aids in optimizing and quantizing models for better performance by facilitating a streamlined flow that incorporates several key enhancements through the conversion process:

1. **Simplified Model Representation**: The SNC format represents a more streamlined and efficient version of the model, making it easier to execute on target hardware like Exynos platforms. This simplified representation results in faster inference times and reduced computational overhead.

2. **Optimized Execution**: Before converting to SNC, models go through an optimization phase where various techniques such as Simplifier and Optimization templates are applied. This ensures that redundant operations are minimized, and the overall computational graph is well-organized for efficient execution.

3. **Effective Quantization**: During the conversion flow, quantization techniques such as Fixed Precision, Smooth Quantization, and Mixed Precision Quantization are applied. These techniques reduce the bit-width of model weights and activations, decreasing memory usage and increasing execution speed while maintaining model accuracy.

4. **Evaluation and Validation**: The conversion process includes performance evaluation stages to ensure that the quality of inference remains consistent across optimizations and quantizations. This helps validate that the converted SNC model still meets the original model's performance requirements.

Overall, the conversion from CNNX to SNC, combined with these optimization and quantization techniques, ensures that the model is not only efficient to execute but also tailored to leverage the hardware accelerations provided by Exynos platforms, thereby enhancing the overall performance of the model in deployment scenarios.",The answer to given question is not present in context,0.29766,0.00571,0.17216,

# Introduction to Exynos AI High-Level Toolchain (EHT)

EHT** is a software that provides optimization techniques for neural networks, including computer vision (CV) models, large language models (LLM), and large vision models (LVM). This software takes models as input and offers functionalities such as quantization and model optimization to generate SNC models.
## System overview diagram; Section: # **How to use**
## **Detailed explanation for elt yaml file**
Content:
perf_estimator : dict**
- **O2_enable : bool** : O2 optimization (true or false)
- **O2_fm_forwarding : bool** : feature-map forwarding (true or false)
- **SEG : bool** : Set true if input model is Deeplab V3+
- **SSD : bool** : Set true if input model is SSD detection
- **bit_width_factor_FM : int** : Select feature map bit width factor (1 or 2)
- **bit_width_factor_FP16 : bool** : Set bit width factor as floating point (true or false)
- **bit_width_factor_weight : int** : Select weight bit width factor (1 or 2)
- **core_num : int** : 1 for single core, 2 for instance-1
- **device : str** : Select device type [Gen-3, Gen-4, Gen-5, Gen-5a]

- **json_report : bool** : Enable report json format","Users can use the EHT module for Mixed Precision Quantization (MPQ) by specifying the activation names or operators in the quantizer configuration. The quantizer module within the EHT offers this capability by allowing users to define different precision levels for different parts of the model.
Here is how it can be done:

1. **Mixed Precision by Activation Name:** Users can specify the precision for specific activation names within the model. This allows various parts of the model to use different precisions based on the specified names.

2. **Mixed Precision by Operator:** Users can define precisions for different types of operators. For instance, if the user sets the ""Add"" operator to INT4, all outputs of the ""Add"" operators are quantized to INT4.

These configurations are done via the EHT YAML file, where users define which activations or operators should have specific precisions different from the rest of the model. The key parameters within the YAML file related to the quantizer are:
- **mpq_operator_dict:** A dictionary to specify the operators and precision to be quantized differently.
- **precision_weight:** To set the precision for weights (e.g., int8, int16, fp16).
- **precision_activation:** To set the precision for activations (e.g., int8, int16, fp16).

This approach ensures an efficient quantization process, adapting the precision needs based on the model's specific parts, leading to potentially better performance and resource optimization.",Users can apply mixed precision quantization to models by specifying activation names or operators using the EHT module.,0.7375,0.0099,0.37962,

- CV
- LVM
- LLM
**quantizer : dict**
- **precision_weight : str** : precision of weight(ex. int8, int16, fp16)
- **precision_activation : str** : precision of activation(ex. int8, int16, fp16)

- **mpq_operator_dict : dict** : When performing mixed precision quantization, input the operators and precision to be quantized with a precision different from the values specified in precision_weight and precision_activation above.
- **alpha : float** : smoothquant migration strength; Section: Quantizer
# Quantizer
## Advanced Quantization Methods
Content:
Currently supported advanced quantization methods are as follows.
- Softmax Bias Correction (https://arxiv.org/abs/2309.01729)

column2: - A method that add a float bias to Softmax output layer to reduce the performance degradation caused by quantization

column1: - SmoothQuant (https://arxiv.org/abs/2211.10438)

column2: - A method that smooths the activation outliers by offline migrating the quantization difficulty from activations to weights with a mathematically equivalent transformation

column1: - Cross Layer Equalization (https://arxiv.org/abs/1906.04721)

column2: - A method that tune the weights range of the channels in one tensor to reduce quantization error; Section: Model Requirements and Constraints

column1: # Model Requirements and Constraints
## CNNX model
Content:
### activation encodings & param encodings

Encodings information for quantization is given as a json data. For each ONNX activation & params name, bitwidth, dtype, and quantization parameters(min, max, offset, scale, is_symmetric) are given in this part.
### quantizer_args
Global quantization information is given on this part including per_channel_quantization and quantization scheme.
### modules

Module information after EHT optimizer is given on this part. Under the module name as a key, SNC layer information(SNC_OP, SNC_params) and ONNX element related to the module(Elements) are given.; Section: Model Requirements and Constraints
# Model Requirements and Constraints
## CNNX model
Content:
Content:
Simulator conducts inference on a CNNX model, which contains an ONNX model file and a quantization information encodings file. It can check output and intermediate tensors during execution.

Quantized inference is performed using _simulated quantization_. Simulated quantization provides the capability to mimic the effects of quantized operations. Floating point values are clipped and divided into several ranges, and values within each range are converted to the same value, simulating the quantization process.

Simulator includes the following features(with example codes):","The Mixed Precision Quantization (MPQ) API in EHT's quantizer aids precision tweaks in a quantized CNNX model by allowing users to specify different levels of precision for various parts of the model. This API provides the flexibility to assign different precisions to specific activations and weights.

For instance, you can choose to quantize certain activation functions or weights at a higher precision while keeping other parts at a lower precision. This can be done for either specific activation or weight names or by defining precisions for different types of operators. This approach enables users to optimize the model by balancing the trade-off between computational efficiency and model accuracy.
Additionally, the MPQ debug API allows users to experiment by selecting different activation and weight precisions, enabling users to fine-tune their models effectively.

Overall, the MPQ API provides a powerful tool for managing precision in a quantized CNNX model, allowing for detailed customization and optimization of a model's performance.",The MPQ API aids precision tweaks in a quantized CNNX model by allowing users to select different activations and weights and assign them varying levels of precision.,0.9,0.00694,0.45088,
How does real-time synchronization work in the File Directory feature of the Remote Streaming Service?,"Section: # [File Directory Management]
Content:
The File Directory feature in the Remote Streaming Service enables you to access and manage files on the remote device.
Rules for using File directory feature:
- Double-click the folders to access them.
- Double-click the captured or uploaded files from the file directory to download them to your PC.
- The file directory is synchronized in real-time with the file browser application of the device and the file updates are immediately reflected.
- You cannot access the file directory path.

column2: To use the File Directory feature:

column1: - Double-click any folder to access its location.
- Use the Back to navigate to the parent folder.
- Use the forward button to navigate to the previous folder.
- After uploading the files, access the /sdcard/download/ directory and double-click the uploaded files to download them.
- After capturing the files, access the /sdcard/image/ directory and double-click the captured files to download them.

If a connection attempt is made from another location, a pop-up message indicates a new connection has been detected. Click OK to redirect to the Device Farm page, while the new connection will continue to use the service.

- A pop-up message for service extension appears 15 minutes before the end of the service usage. This can be extended up to 2 hours of additional time within the maximum daily usage time of 8 hours. If there are not enough credits, only the possible extension duration is displayed. Click OK to extend the usage time based on the additional time that is selected. Click Cancel to end the service usage and a pop-up message indicates Service usage time has expired. Click OK to redirect to the Device Farm page.

Content:
The Remote Streaming Service feature allows you to remotely control devices and test customized applications.
Overview of the Remote Streaming Service page:

- Status area: This area is located at the top-left of the page and displays information about the current system status that includes the processor name, connection status, and the remaining usage time.
- Stop button: This button is located at the top-right of the page and it is used to terminate the streaming session.
- Device Control Area: This area is located on the left of the page and it contains buttons for controlling device functions such as mute and screen rotation.

- Device Screen Area: This area is located on the left of the page and displays the device screen. It allows you to control the device by clicking it with your mouse thus simulating a touch experience.; Content:
# [Streaming Service Termination]
To stop the Remote Streaming Service:
1. Click Stop from the Remote Streaming Service area.
2. In the pop-up message that is displayed, confirm the termination to end the session.
# [Returning to Streaming Page]
If you want to return to streaming after exiting from the streaming screen without clicking Stop:
1. Find the reservation you want to resume and click Connect.
2. You will be redirected to the main streaming page, and you can resume streaming from the point where you left off.; Section: # [Command Shell Access]
Content:
The Command Shell feature in the Remote Streaming Service enables you to control the device through command-line inputs.
Rules for using Command shell feature:
- Only commands necessary for device control are supported.
- Commands can be continuously entered similar to entering commands in a PC command window.
- Commands can be sent by pressing Enter key or clicking Send.
- Click Command Shell to open a modal window to enter the commands and control the device.

column2: To use the Command Shell feature:

column1: - Enter the commands and press Enter key on the keyboard.
- Enter the commands and click Send.
- Click Command Shell to open the modal window.
- Enter the commands in the modal window and press Enter key on the keyboard.
- Enter the commands in the modal window and click Send.; Section: # [Uploading File/APP]
Content:
The Uploading File feature is available in the Remote Streaming Service, and enables File transfer from your local storage to the device for various purposes.
Rules for using Uploading File feature:
- Remote Streaming Service supports most of the file types. APK files are automatically installed and launched on the device.
- If an APK file does not install after upload, it may be an unsupported APK.
- APK files are not uploaded to the device storage separately.
- All files other than APKs are uploaded to the /sdcard/download/ directory.
- Files up to 200 MB can be uploaded with the total upload capacity of up to 2 GB.

- Files can either be dragged and dropped from the local directory to the upload area or they can be selected using the file dialog that is launched when you click the upload area located at the right corner of the screen.

column2: To use the Uploading File feature:; Section: # [Screenshot / Recording]

column1: Content:
The Screenshot feature in the Remote Streaming Service enables you to capture images of the device screen for documentation or review purposes.
Rules for using Screenshot feature:
1. Click Screenshot to capture the device screen. The captured screenshots are downloaded to your PC and saved to the /sdcard/image/ directory.
2. Click Screenshot to capture the device screen as an image file.

column2: The Record feature in the Remote Streaming Service enables you to record the device screen in real-time and save it in a video file format.

column1: Rules for using Record feature:
1. Click Record to start the device screen recording. After the recording starts, this button changes to Stop, and it displays the recording time.
2. Click Stop to end the device screen recording. The recorded file is downloaded to your PC and saved to the /sdcard/image/ directory.
3. Click Record to start the recording of the device screen.
4. Click Stop to save and end the recording.; Section: # [Logcat Window]
Content:
The Logcat Window feature in the Remote Streaming Service records the usage history of the remote service in real-time and enables you to review the usage logs.
Rules for using Logcat window feature:
- Logcat starts recording immediately after the remote service connection is established.
- Logs can be downloaded only when the remote service is connected.
- Logs cannot be downloaded after the remote service is disconnected.
- Click Log download to save the log file to your PC.

column2: To use the Logcat Window feature:

column1: - Navigate to the Logcat Window section.
- Review system logs and debugging information as required.
- Click Download to save the system log file to your PC.; Content:

How does Samsung's advanced real-device testing service enhance the quality of models and apps?,"Content:
For Banner:

Samsung’s advanced real-device testing service powered by Exynos enhances the quality of your models and apps by connecting them across diverse devices. This leads to a smarter and more innovative outcome.
Getting Started

This guide describes the complete process of reserving and managing devices within the Device Farm, thus ensuring a smooth and efficient user experience.; Question: Please tell us about the advantages of ENN SDK compared to other SDKs?

Answer: The AI Toolset provided by each chipset is optimized for each chipset. ENN SDK is also optimized for Exynos chipset. Additionally, it is also used as an optimization tool for Samsung mobile device. Additionally, I think it will be a great advantage for developers to be able to reflect the voices of domestic developers and have the opportunity to participate in development like this program.; Question: Please tell us about the AI Challenger.

Answer: Samsung S.LSI's AI Challenger, a key part of the SEED AI initiative, is dedicated to driving technological innovation through artificial intelligence. Central to the program is the Exynos ENN SDK, an advanced toolkit by Samsung S.LSI designed to facilitate AI model creation and optimization. This versatile SDK is instrumental for developing a wide range of AI applications, from image recognition to complex predictive analytics, and is a vital resource for developers seeking to craft impactful AI solutions in various sectors. Continually refined and supported by Samsung's dedicated ML team, the Exynos ENN SDK remains at the forefront of the ever-evolving digital landscape, meeting the dynamic needs of the AI industry. Through the AI Challenger, Samsung S.LSI showcases its commitment to leading AI advancements and nurturing a vibrant community of AI developers, propelling the industry towards a future where AI is integral to technological innovation and progress.; Question: Please tell us about the ENN SDK.

Answer: ENN SDK is a software development kit for the Exynos chipset developed by Samsung S.LSI. It is designed to optimize and implement AI and machine learning models on Exynos-based device. Key features include model optimization for Exynos chipsets, support for various AI algorithms, and user-friendly interface improvement. It is primarily aimed at use on mobile devices and aims to provide developers with efficient tools through continuous updates and improvement.; Question: I would like to know the advantages of Exynos 2200, the base chipset of the reference device provided by First AI Challenger managers.

Answer: Console quality graphics now on mobile with the Exynos 2200 mobile processor. The Samsung Xclipse GPU sets to usher in a new era and completely change the way we experience mobile gaming. Playtime is well and truly over.; Question: I want to know the main summary of Samsung Exynos 2200.

Answer: Samsung Electronics introduces the Exynos 2200, a premium mobile processor featuring the Samsung Xclipse GPU based on AMD RDNA 2 architecture, crafted using a 4-nanometer EUV process. This processor enhances mobile gaming, social media, and photography, offering the first mobile hardware-accelerated ray tracing for realistic lighting and variable rate shading for smoother gameplay. It boasts an upgraded neural processing unit (NPU), Arm's latest Armv9 CPU cores for superior performance and security, and a fast 5G modem compliant with 3GPP Release 16. With integrated Secure Element (iSE) and robust encryption, it ensures data security. The processor's ISP supports up to 200MP resolution, AI-integrated camera functionalities for professional-quality images, an advanced codec for up to 8K video, and a display solution with HDR10+ and up to 144Hz refresh rates, ensuring a comprehensive and immersive visual experience.; Question: I want to know about the AI Challenger.

Answer: The AI Challenger is an open innovation type of developer program that uses and develops AI SDK using Samsung S.LSI Exynos ENN SDK.; Question: Please tell us about the company that actually developed EDS Assistant.
Answer: Samsung S.LSI plans and supervises EDS Assistant and ThunderSoft Korea supervises the actual development.; Section: # Exynos Chipsets

# [Overview]

This guide aims to enhance users' understanding of the Device Farm and ensures to provide a smooth experience with the system by providing detailed information on the rules and usage of each feature.; Section: # [Remote Service Launch]
Content:
The [Start now] feature enables users to instantly access and utilize the Remote Service.
Rules for using [Start now] feature:
- Login Required: You must login first and click [Start now] to access the device.
- Credit Required: You must have enough credits to use the device (1 credit = 30 mins). For more information on obtaining additional credits, refer to [Credit Management].
- No Available Devices: If there are no devices currently available, proceed with the device reservation using [Reservation] feature.
- Maximum Number of Reservations: The maximum number of device reservations allowed is 5.
- Maximum Usage Time: The maximum usage time available through [Start Now] is 4 hours.
- Duration Settings: The duration can be set in increments of 30 minutes up to 4 hours and adjusted according to available credits.
- Credit Update: After selecting the duration, the required credits are updated and displayed.

If you want to return to streaming after exiting from the streaming screen without clicking Stop:
1. Find the reservation you want to resume and click Connect.

- Logs cannot be downloaded after the remote service is disconnected.

Content:
The Remote Streaming Service feature allows you to remotely control devices and test customized applications.
Overview of the Remote Streaming Service page:

- Status area: This area is located at the top-left of the page and displays information about the current system status that includes the processor name, connection status, and the remaining usage time.
- Stop button: This button is located at the top-right of the page and it is used to terminate the streaming session.
- Device Control Area: This area is located on the left of the page and it contains buttons for controlling device functions such as mute and screen rotation.

- Device Screen Area: This area is located on the left of the page and displays the device screen. It allows you to control the device by clicking it with your mouse thus simulating a touch experience.; Section: # [Command Shell Access]
Content:
The Command Shell feature in the Remote Streaming Service enables you to control the device through command-line inputs.
Rules for using Command shell feature:
- Only commands necessary for device control are supported.
- Commands can be continuously entered similar to entering commands in a PC command window.
- Commands can be sent by pressing Enter key or clicking Send.
- Click Command Shell to open a modal window to enter the commands and control the device.

column2: To use the Command Shell feature:

column1: - Enter the commands and press Enter key on the keyboard.
- Enter the commands and click Send.
- Click Command Shell to open the modal window.
- Enter the commands in the modal window and press Enter key on the keyboard.
- Enter the commands in the modal window and click Send.; Section: # [Credit Management]
Content:
Credits are necessary to use the Service on the Device Farm page. Following is the method to obtain the required credits:
- Credit Allocation:
- 10 credits are received for logging in once per day.
- One credit is received for each Forum post (up to a maximum of five credits per day).
- 10 credits are received for each Lab project that is created (up to a maximum of 20 credits per day).
- Two credits are received for each NNC Convert (up to a maximum of 10 credits per day).
- Deduction: One credit is deducted for every 30 minutes of Remote Service use.
- Reservation Credits: Credits used for reservations are not refunded if reservation is not connected within 30 minutes. The canceled reservations will refund all credits.
- Service Stop: Credits are deducted at a rate of 1 credit per 30-minute for service after the reservation time, and the remaining credits are refunded.
- Validity: Free credits expire after 90 days without any notification.
- Credit Balance: This is updated as soon as the credits are used.
- Management: You can verify the expiration details, acquisition, and usage from the My Credit menu of the My Page.; Section: # [File Directory Management]
Content:
The File Directory feature in the Remote Streaming Service enables you to access and manage files on the remote device.
Rules for using File directory feature:
- Double-click the folders to access them.
- Double-click the captured or uploaded files from the file directory to download them to your PC.
- The file directory is synchronized in real-time with the file browser application of the device and the file updates are immediately reflected.
- You cannot access the file directory path.

column2: To use the File Directory feature:

column1: - Double-click any folder to access its location.
- Use the Back to navigate to the parent folder.
- Use the forward button to navigate to the previous folder.
- After uploading the files, access the /sdcard/download/ directory and double-click the uploaded files to download them.
- After capturing the files, access the /sdcard/image/ directory and double-click the captured files to download them.

- No Available Devices: If there are no devices currently available, proceed with the device reservation using [Reservation] feature.
- Maximum Number of Reservations: The maximum number of device reservations allowed is 5.
- Maximum Usage Time: The maximum usage time available through [Start Now] is 4 hours.

- Credit Update: After selecting the duration, the required credits are updated and displayed.
- Starting Service: After setting the Duration and confirming the credits, click Start to initiate the Remote Service.

Content:
The Uploading File feature is available in the Remote Streaming Service, and enables File transfer from your local storage to the device for various purposes.
Rules for using Uploading File feature:
- Remote Streaming Service supports most of the file types. APK files are automatically installed and launched on the device.
- If an APK file does not install after upload, it may be an unsupported APK.
- APK files are not uploaded to the device storage separately.
- All files other than APKs are uploaded to the /sdcard/download/ directory.
- Files up to 200 MB can be uploaded with the total upload capacity of up to 2 GB.

- Files can either be dragged and dropped from the local directory to the upload area or they can be selected using the file dialog that is launched when you click the upload area located at the right corner of the screen.

Content:
The [Start now] feature enables users to instantly access and utilize the Remote Service.
Rules for using [Start now] feature:
- Login Required: You must login first and click [Start now] to access the device.
- Credit Required: You must have enough credits to use the device (1 credit = 30 mins). For more information on obtaining additional credits, refer to [Credit Management].
- No Available Devices: If there are no devices currently available, proceed with the device reservation using [Reservation] feature.
- Maximum Number of Reservations: The maximum number of device reservations allowed is 5.
- Maximum Usage Time: The maximum usage time available through [Start Now] is 4 hours.
- Duration Settings: The duration can be set in increments of 30 minutes up to 4 hours and adjusted according to available credits.
- Credit Update: After selecting the duration, the required credits are updated and displayed.
- Starting Service: After setting the Duration and confirming the credits, click Start to initiate the Remote Service.
1. After you are logged in, click [Start now].
2. Select the required duration.
3. Click Start to initiate the Remote Service.; Content:
